tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Displacement City, outreach worker Greg Cook and street nurse Cathy Crowe present the stories of frontline workers, advocates, and people living without homes during the pandemic. The book uses prose, poetry, and photography to document lived experiences of homelessness, responses to the housing crisis, efforts to fight back for homes, and possible solutions to move Toronto forward. Contributors provide particular insight into policies affecting Indigenous peoples and how the legacy of colonialism and displacement reached a critical point during the pandemic. Offering rich stories of care, mutual aid, and solidarity, Displacement City provides a vivid account of a humanitarian disaster.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspectszOntariozToronto. 0aHomeless personsxServices forzOntariozToronto. 0aHomelessnesszOntariozToronto. 0aHousingzOntariozToronto. 0aShelters for the homelesszOntariozToronto. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aCOVID-19.  aToronto.  acolonialism.  acolonization.  adisplacement.  aencampments.  aeviction.  agentrification.  aharm reduction.  ahome.  ahomelessness.  apandemic.  apoetry.  ashelter system.  ashelters.  asocial housing.  asocial work.  atreaties.1 aBlack, Derrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleary, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Greg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrowe, Ca